  "prompt": "What is creamy layer?",
  "response": "The term \"creamy layer\" refers to the relatively wealthier and better-educated members of a traditionally disadvantaged or backward community, particularly in the context of India. It denotes those individuals within the Other Backward Classes (OBC) who have reached a level of socio-economic status that makes them relatively well-off compared to others in their community.\n\nThe concept is significant in the context of reservations and affirmative action policies. In India, certain communities, including the OBCs, are provided reservations in education, employment, and other areas as a means to ensure social equity and upliftment of historically marginalized groups. The creamy layer is intended to be excluded from these benefits, ensuring that the reservations reach those who are genuinely in need and preventing more advantaged individuals from using these measures to perpetuate advantage across generations.\n\nCriteria for determining the creamy layer typically include income, professional status, and educational attainment, with specific thresholds set by governmental policies.",
